@Mottie - Thank you for the feedback. The second demo prompted me to investigate my issues further. It turns out that I was failing to call "update" after adding additional child rows. This was causing the sort itself to behave very strangely with the multiple child rows.

Calling update (as apparently I should have been all along) fixes the issue.

Thanks for your help!

Ok, [here is an example](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/uwZc2/32/) using filltext.com as a data source, so the demo won't sort or allow filtering but it should give you an idea of how it could be done.

```js
$(function(){
	var $table = $('table'),
		size = 5;

	$table
		.tablesorter({
			theme: 'blue',
			widthFixed: true,
			widgets: ['zebra', 'columns']
		})
		.tablesorterPager({
			container: $(".pager"),
			size: size,
			// set to false otherwise it remembers setting from other jsFiddle demos
			savePages: false,
			ajaxUrl: "http://www.filltext.com/?callback=?",
			customAjaxUrl: function(table, url) {
				// need to dynamically update page size
				// since adding 'rows : size' in ajaxObject.data doesn't
				// dynamically update the size
                // take size X 2, so we grab extra data for the second tbody
				table.config.pager.ajaxObject.data.rows = table.config.pager.size * 2;
				return url;
			},
			ajaxObject: {
				data: {
					// rows   : size, // this doesn't work because size can't be updated dynamically
					'#'    : '{index}',
					'ID'   : '{randomNumberLength|3}',
					'First': '{firstName}',
					'Last' : '{lastName}',
					'State': '{usState|abbr}',
					'Info' : '{lorem|3}'
				}
			},
			ajaxProcessing: function (data, table) {
				if (data) {
					var col, row, txt,
                        c = table.config,
						// make # column show correct value
						index = c.pager.page,
						headers = [ '#', 'ID', 'First', 'Last', 'State', 'Info' ],
						len = headers.length,
						json = {},
						rows = [];
					size = data.length;
					for (row = 0; row < size; row++){
						txt = '<tr>';
						for (col = 0; col < len; col++) {
							txt += '<td>';
                            // make # column show correct index
							txt += col === 0 ? index * size + row + col + 1 : data[ row ][ headers[col] ];
							txt += '</td>';
						}
						rows.push( txt + '</tr>' );
					}
					json.total = 100; // only allow 100 rows in total
					json.filteredRows = 100; // no filtering
					json.headers = headers;
                    // add data to first tbody (only include 1/2 of the rows)
                    c.$tbodies.eq(0).html( rows.splice(0,size/2).join('') );
                    // add data to second tbody - c.$tbodies does not include info tbodies
                    // so the index only increases by one here
                    // add remaining rows
                    c.$tbodies.eq(1).html( rows.join('') );
					// Don't return rows with the json
					return json;
				}
			},
			output: '{startRow} to {endRow} of {filteredRows} ({totalRows})'
		});
});
```

Ok, I think the easiest solution would be to separate the departments into separate tables, then add a class name to each header & set a width for that column - [here is an example](http://jsfiddle.net/abkNM/5895/)

HTML (class name added to each `<th>`)

```html
<thead>
    <tr>
        <th class="anumeric">AlphaNumeric</th>
        <th class="numeric">Numeric</th>
        <th class="animals">Animals</th>
        <th class="url">Sites</th>
    </tr>
</thead>
```

CSS

```css
.anumeric { width: 30%; }
.numeric { width: 10%; }
.animals { width: 20%; }
.url { width: 40%; }
```

When initializing tablesorter, it would be optional to include the `widthFixed` option. 

```js
$(function () {
    $('table').tablesorter({
        theme: 'blue',
        widthFixed: true // optional
    });
});
```

What this option does is adds a `<col>` for each column with a set percentage width, so if you happen to skip a few columns widths with the HTML/CSS, this will lock in the initial proportional column width and keep all the tables in alignment (unless they start out with different column widths).

The reason you're seeing a change from v1.16.5 is because the time parser now extracts out the time in case you manually set the time parser on a full date column like "12/18/2015 6:30 PM" - it will now only target the "6:30 PM"

So, if you look at the [`filter_function`](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#widget-filter-functions) parameters:

```js
// function variables:
// e = exact text from cell
// n = normalized value returned by the column parser
// f = search filter input value
// i = column index
// $r = jQuery element of current row
// c = table.config
// data = combined filter data
0: function( e, n, f, i, $r ) { ... }
```

You will see that `n` is the normalized (or parsed) data, so if the time parser is being detected - I'm not sure why since the times in the example have two times with a comma separator - it will parse and save that time as the [number of milliseconds since the epoch](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date/getTime).

To get exact table cell content, use `e`.

