@jacksonloper:  Admittedly, I have done this same workaround you are proposing myself before.  It's not in `dill` as it's making some pretty severe assumptions that are not good in some cases.  So, under that vague warning, I have been hesitant to add this to `dill`.  However, you are right… if the user **chooses** this behavior, why not allow it?  There is indeed a `dill.settings`, which is a `dict` of variants for how `dill` will behave under `dump` and `load` for certain objects -- so that would be an excellent place for this kind of variant.

@matsjoyce: `sudo` is funny, but I don't like the name.

So, if this seems like it will fall into one of the existing `settings`, then let's do that.  If it doesn't, then let's come up with a good name for it, that might generalize beyond this particular use case.  Like maybe there are some other variants that have the same flavor that make sense to bundle together into a single setting (i.e. drop objects that don't pickle under a `dump_session`?) Then, yes, a PR should be submitted by all means.

So this was mostly a selfish concern about the platform-specific osx testing, which is orthogonal-ish to your thoughts on the rust testing above, and the right answer may involve moving testing between shards, or something. Since the rust testing completes extremely quickly, I was thinking it wouldn't tend to push back integration testing a significant amount -- but on the other hand, osx platform-specific testing can be quite significant, for certain PRs. I'm not sure that needs to justify moving it earlier, because I can always just restart the integration test shards manually to do this, but it seemed like the benefit outweighed waiting not-that-much-longer (also a subjective judgement) for the integration test shards.

However, I don't feel like I really know how to compare the relative utility of tests completing earlier or later in a global sense, and I don't consider my own needs to outweigh those of most people hacking on pants. I also don't know the cost model -- if we were to create an extra osx shard to run the platform-specific testing alone, I'm assuming that's more we end up paying to travis. I would be totally satisfied if we were to keep the order the same -- I was just thinking it might be a useful tradeoff to make.

